# Code coverage — product assemblies only

## Intent

CI and local **`dotnet test … --collect:"XPlat Code Coverage"`** exist to measure **production** (**`ArchLucid.*`** libraries and hosts), not test project source. Test assemblies are **hosts** for Coverlet; they must not inflate or dilute merged coverage.

## Invariants (do not regress)

1. **`coverage.runsettings`** — Keep a Coverlet **`Exclude`** that drops **test assemblies**, e.g. `<Exclude>[*Tests]*</Exclude>` (plus any narrower product exclusions already listed). Do not remove the test-assembly exclusion to “fix” gates.
2. **`Directory.Build.props`** (repo root and template copies that build **`.Tests`** projects) — Keep **`ExcludeFromCodeCoverage`** assembly attribute for projects whose **`MSBuildProjectName` ends with `.Tests`**. New test projects must follow the **`.Tests`** suffix or get the same attribute explicitly.
3. **`coverlet.collector`** stays on test projects — it is required for collection; excluding test code from the report is not the same as removing the package.
4. Do not add **`[ExcludeFromCodeCoverage]`** to test **classes** individually unless there is an exceptional case (prefer assembly-level exclusion for normal xUnit/FA test types).

## When editing

- If you add a new **test** project pattern (e.g. not ending in **`.Tests`**), extend **`coverage.runsettings`** and **`Directory.Build.props`** conditions in the same PR.
- If you change Coverlet’s filter syntax, run a local **`dotnet test`** with **`coverage.runsettings`** and confirm merged Cobertura **packages** do not list **`*Tests`** assemblies as measured product scope.
